arXiv:2512.19051v1 Announce Type: cross Abstract: Recently, Sharoglazova et al. claimed to have proven a violation of the basic tenet of Bohmian mechanics, namely the phase-speed relation $\vec{v}(\vec{r},t)= rac{\hbar}{m}\vec{
abla}S(\vec{r},t)$. Here, $S(\vec{r},t)$ is the (real) phase of the wave function $\psi(\vec{r},t)=ho^{ rac{1}{2}}(\vec{r},t)e^{iS(\vec{r},t)}$. In a nutshell, they have measured the speed of a claimed evanescent wave, which is real and therefore must have $\vec{
abla}S=\vec{0}$. However, Fig. 2 clearly shows a density motion from one waveguide to the other, implying a nonzero density current, $\vec{j}(\vec{r},t)= rac{\hbar}{2mi}\Im(\psi^*\vec{
abla}\psi)$. If we combine this evidence with the mathematical identity $\vec{
abla}S= rac{m}{ho}\vec{j}$, we should instead conclude that $\vec{
abla}S
eq\vec{0}$. So, where does this apparent inconsistency come from?
